\cf2 It\'92s not an enormous leap from these videos to home cooks who try to build their followings on TikTok or Facebook by showing off their best quick-and-easy recipe hacks. Just as Tasty\'92s success has been a\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 significant boon
\fs39\fsmilli19800 \'a0to BuzzFeed\'92s bottom line, viral cooking videos can help their creators amass an audience, sell sponsored content, make endorsement deals, and run ads. For the people who do the best job figuring out what others want to see\'97by Tasty\'92s example, it often seems to be quick, comforting, nostalgic foods\'97and how to get it in front of them, virality can mean realizing the dream of quitting a 9-to-5 job to work for themselves.\
To achieve this, recipes that use cheap, widely accessible, shelf-stable ingredients appear to be a good bet. America is not a nation of super-skilled cooks. Most Americans say they\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 don\'92t consistently enjoy the activity
\fs39\fsmilli19800 . The country\'92s food system was industrialized generations ago, which means that most people have little relationship to where their food comes from, and many lack the kitchen skills that might have been a basic necessity for their grandparents. That itself is a marketing opportunity for agricultural conglomerates; separating people from their understanding of what they eat creates a void that can be filled with convenience products and fast food.
\f1\i \

\f0\i0 For many people, this way of eating isn\'92t just a cultural reality, but an economic and practical need. Canned goods and processed foods are cheap and plentiful in places where fresh produce often isn\'92t, and they take some of the prep work out of cleaning and chopping for people who are exhausted or physically unable to do it, or who didn\'92t get much cooking instruction from their own exhausted parents. The Food Network personality Sandra Lee built an empire out of this style of \'93semi-homemade\'94 cooking after growing up poor, and is, in some sense, also a foremother of the accidentally viral cooking video\'97some of her recipes, like her\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 infamous Kwanzaa cake
\fs39\fsmilli19800 , test the bounds of credulity.\
Watching someone in a tastefully appointed luxury kitchen cook with the kinds of foods that affluent Americans frequently eschew can be disorienting; it\'92s often unclear how much mockery, if any, lurks beneath the surface of any particular video. The ones that take place in normal-person kitchens usually seem more sincere. Either way, it\'92s easy for things to go awry. Sometimes these amateurs run afoul of\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 how much dairy
\fs39\fsmilli19800 \'a0the wider internet is willing to tolerate, or they put\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 too many soft canned goods
\fs39\fsmilli19800 \'a0in a crock pot set to High. If you know better, the errors are indeed disgusting. If you don\'92t, maybe Spaghetti-Os are pie filling.\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 Spaghetti pie
\fs39\fsmilli19800 , after all, is a recipe that sometimes lands in the cookbooks of celebrity chefs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
For viewers who don\'92t genuinely want help constructing a fast dinner out of shelf-stable ingredients, why keep coming back for more? The internet is brimming with absurdity of all types, so it\'92s all the more notable that these gross videos seem to be impervious to fluctuating tastes or the whims of an algorithm. If you can\'92t go viral on your own, all you have to do is find someone absolutely bricking an attempt at pasta Alfredo, slap on a one-liner about the crimes its creator has commited, and virality is yours for the taking.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

