\f0\i0 \cf2 The internet, of course, is just as useful for fracturing shared realities as it is for creating them. I still don\'92t know whether Flom was joking, and I\'92m not even sure what it would mean for her to be joking anymore. Her Facebook page, where the video originated, is full of nonculinary pranks identified as such\'97things like tricking her frequent co-star into grabbing a cactus. But\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 the page\'92s food section
\fs39\fsmilli19800 \'a0simply advertises videos of \'93kitchen fun and crazy recipe hacks,\'94 many of which have tens of millions of views. There and on her TikTok account, she has leaned hard into straight-faced gross-out food since the Spaghetti-Os pie went viral, doing things like reconstituting potato chips into mashed potatoes or frying a steak in a thick casing of butter.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 When you look at Flom\'92s videos back-to-back, in the context of all the other things she\'92s done in apparent bids for social-media virality, she clearly\'a0
\f1\i is
\f0\i0 \'a0trolling\'97the butter arms and all the other weird little details are too conspicuous to be anything but provocative. But that\'92s still not quite the same thing as joking. Some of the ghastly recipes seem like they work on some level, like her \'93peach cobbler\'94 made out of Cinnamon Toast Crunch, canned peaches, and cake mix. It looks like a real dessert when it comes out of the oven, and the people who taste it on camera don\'92t flinch before singing its praises. In the comments, viewers report trying it and loving it, and they recommend tweaks to the recipe for others.\
One of Flom\'92s\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 more outrageous videos
\fs39\fsmilli19800 , which demonstrates a recipe called Sprite pie, melds two real parts of food history pioneered by the poor: the Depression-era water pie, which mimicked a custard when eggs and milk were scarce, and the use of soda to sweeten desserts and lighten their texture, a long-standing part of\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 Black southern cooking
\fs39\fsmilli19800 . The recipe had been bandied about among food TikTokers before Flom uploaded her version to Facebook, and one popular DIY chef on YouTube has racked up\'a0
\fs39\fsmilli19600 nearly 1 million views
\fs39\fsmilli19800 \'a0proving that the concoction does indeed work. The filling sets up into a custard, and, apparently, it is sweet and satisfying.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Is Flom joking, or is she serious? Yes. Everything on the internet is a joke until it\'92s not anymore.\
